You are executing the 01-High-Level-Design skill. Your mandate is to transform the SRS requirements into a system-level architecture document with Mermaid diagrams per IEEE 1016-2009 Sec 5.

1. Read ../output/SRS_Draft.md (all sections) and ../project_context/tech_stack.md. Optionally read ../output/PRD.md if it exists. Log all file paths. Halt if SRS_Draft.md or tech_stack.md is missing.
2. Determine the Architectural Style from tech_stack.md and SRS Section 3.4 constraints: monolith, microservices, serverless, layered, or event-driven. State the choice with a rationale paragraph citing specific SRS constraints.
3. Generate a System Context Diagram using Mermaid C4Context syntax. Include the system boundary, external actors from SRS Section 2.0, external systems from SRS Section 3.1, and labeled data exchanges between them. Every diagram node and edge SHALL have a descriptive label.
4. Generate a Component Architecture Diagram using Mermaid graph TD syntax. Decompose into layers: Presentation, Business Logic, Data Access, Infrastructure. For each component state its name, responsibility (one sentence), and interfaces exposed.
5. Generate a Deployment Topology Diagram using Mermaid syntax. Map every component to an infrastructure target (server, container, cloud service). Include ports, protocols, and TLS configuration from SRS Section 3.1. Every diagram node and edge SHALL have a descriptive label.
6. Generate Data Flow Diagrams using Mermaid flowchart syntax. Show data entry points, transformation steps, storage locations, and retrieval paths for each major data flow identified in the SRS functional requirements.
7. Generate a Technology Decisions table with columns: Decision, Options Considered, Choice, Rationale. Technology decisions SHALL cite SRS constraints as rationale for every choice made.
8. Document Integration Points for each external system in SRS Section 3.1: system name, protocol, authentication method, data format, and error handling strategy.
9. Document Cross-Cutting Concerns. Authentication and authorization SHALL reference SRS Section 3.5.3. Logging SHALL define log levels and structured format. Error handling SHALL define global strategy and retry policies. Caching SHALL define layers, invalidation, and TTL policies. Cross-cutting concerns SHALL reference specific SRS sections.
10. Generate a Traceability table mapping HLD Component to SRS Section to Requirement IDs. The traceability table SHALL link every HLD component to at least one SRS requirement. Write the completed document to ../output/HLD.md. Log section count and component count.
